What is LDL cholesterol? LDL stands for low density lipoprotein. LDL is typically classified as the bad cholesterol. When you have high levels of LDL in your body, it can lead to plaque formation in the arteries. Which ultimately can lead to a cardiovascular incident or a stroke. Why do we have low density lipid proteins in the body? They carry fats through the bloodstream. LDL has high levels of cholesterol and lower levels of protein. Having too high, LDL can lead to plaque formation in the arteries. But, it‚Äôs not about having no cholesterol because we do need cholesterol for certain body functions like building cell membranes, and hormones. But we want to keep the LDL number lower. ##myjourney##cholesterol##hearthealth##highcholesterol##hdl##ldl##gene##genetics##trigliceridos##healthyheart##workout##bloodwork##stressrelief##stress##advocate##health##walk##exercise##vitaminD##omega3

The DASH Diet is supported by numerous studies showing its effectiveness in lowering blood pressure and improving cardiovascular health. It also encourages moderate consumption of nuts, seeds, and legumes. The Heart, Liver, Lungs, Spleen, and Kidneys. These are the 5 Zang or Yin Organs of traditional Chinese medicine. Each represents a sphere of influence that ancient Chinese doctors attributed to each Organ. Some of these functions align with modern medicine, while others do not. Maintaining balance both within and among these 5 Organs is essential to overall health and wellbeing. Liver-Qi stagnation manifests as a feeling of distension of the hypochondrium, chest, epigastrium, and/or abdomen, sighing. melancholy, depression, moodiness, mood swings, anxiety, a feeling of a lump in the throat, irregular periods, distension of breasts before menstruation, and premenstrual tension and irritability. The tongue is normal. The pulse is Wiry, especially on the left side. Liver-Qi stagnation arises primarily from a prolonged state of frustration, repressed anger, or resentment. If left untreated, it can lead to Liver-Blood stasis. The treatment principle is to smooth the Liver and move Qi. This pattern can be treated using acupuncture, herbal medicine, and meditative practices. Regulating sleep, and physical exercise, particularly intense cardiovascular exercise, are also important. Foods that move Qi include green leafy vegetables and pungent foods like turmeric, cumin, black pepper, alliums, basil, rosemary, horseradish, and vinegars. As always, be healthy, be happy. POTS (Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome) is more than just feeling dizzy when you stand up‚Äîit‚Äôs a complex disorder that affects the autonomic nervous system, which controls vital bodily functions. People with POTS experience a rapid increase in heartbeat and other symptoms like fatigue, lightheadedness, and fainting upon standing, which can make daily activities challenging. Despite its impact, POTS is often misunderstood and misdiagnosed. It‚Äôs not just ‚Äòall in your head‚Äô; it‚Äôs a real and physically taxing condition that many struggle with, particularly young women. The symptoms can vary widely from person to person, which means that living with POTS requires not only medical intervention but also a strong support system and significant lifestyle adjustments to manage effectively. It‚Äôs crucial to spread awareness about POTS and build a community where sufferers can share experiences and support each other. Whether you‚Äôve been diagnosed with POTS or know someone who might be silently struggling: your understanding and empathy can make a world of difference. Let‚Äôs stand together to support the POTS community and push for more research and better treatments. üåü If this resonated with you or could help someone you know, please Like, Save, and Share this post. Don‚Äôt forget to Comment with your thoughts or experiences, and Follow us for more insights and updates. Instant Pot Chicken Enchilada Bowl üêî Servings: 4 (2 cups per serving) Ingredients 1 lb. frozen raw chicken breasts, boneless, skinless 1 (10-oz.) can enchilada sauce 3 (12-oz.) bags cauliflower rice 5 medium green onions, sliced 2 cups canned black beans, drained, rinsed ¬Ω cup chopped fresh cilantro, divided use 2 roma tomatoes, chopped into ¬Ω-inch cubes 1 medium ripe avocado, cubed 1 medium lime, quartered Instructions Place chicken breasts and enchilada sauce in an Instant Pot; toss to coat evenly. Cover and seal pot; cook with pressure cooker setting on high for 15 minutes. Release pressure to vent immediately, being careful to avoid escaping steam. The more omega-6 that we take in, the larger amount of inflammation begins to accumulate in the arteries. The body then can use cholesterol and/or calcium to patch up this inflamed endothelial tissue.  This can then lead to more plaque, hardening, stiffness, & stenosis of the arteries which may put you at greater risk for cardiovascular issues. That's why it's so important not to overdo your intake of inflammatory Omega-6 fatty acids and to always make sure that you're balancing them out with the more anti-inflammatory Omega-3s. In a recent conversation with Dr. Suzanne Steinbaum, a leader in preventative cardiology, she talks about a surprising fact that sleep apnea is a risk factor for heart disease. People with sleep apnea often experience pauses in breathing during sleep, leading to decreased oxygen levels in the blood and increased stress on the cardiovascular system. This can result in high blood pressure, irregular heartbeats, and a higher risk of heart attack, stroke, and other cardiovascular problems. Many women are susceptible to sleep apnea and menopausal women are at an even greater risk. To learn more about other risk factors for heart disease in women and how you can take control of your health, listen to the full conversation on your preferred podcast platform! #heartdisease #sleepapnea #cardiology #womenshealth #cardiovascularhealth

Pomegranate, apple, and lemon juice can offer numerous health benefits when consumed as part of a balanced diet. Each of these fruits is rich in essential nutrients and bioactive compounds that can promote overall well-being. Here are some of the potential benefits of drinking pomegranate, apple, and lemon juice: 1. **Rich in Vitamins and Antioxidants**: Pomegranate, apple, and lemon are all excellent sources of vitamins, particularly vitamin C. These vitamins act as antioxidants, which help neutralize harmful free radicals in the body and protect cells from oxidative stress. 2. **Boosts Immune System**: Due to their vitamin C content, these juices can strengthen the immune system, aiding in the body's defense against infections and illnesses. 3. **Heart Health**: Pomegranate and apple juices have been associated with heart health benefits. They may help lower blood pressure, reduce LDL cholesterol levels, and improve overall cardiovascular function. 4. **Anti-Inflammatory Properties**: Pomegranate, apple, and lemon juices contain compounds that possess anti-inflammatory properties, which can be beneficial in reducing inflammation and managing inflammatory conditions. 5. **Digestive Health**: Lemon juice, in particular, is known for its ability to aid digestion. It can help stimulate the production of digestive juices and promote regular bowel movements. 6. **Hydration**: All three juices can contribute to your daily fluid intake, helping to keep you hydrated. 7. **Weight Management**: These juices are generally low in calories and fat, making them a healthier alternative to sugary beverages. As part of a balanced diet, they can support weight management efforts. 8. **Skin Health**: The high vitamin C content in these juices can promote collagen production, which is essential for skin health. It may help maintain skin elasticity and reduce signs of aging. 9. **Improved Blood Circulation**: Pomegranate juice, in particular, has been studied for its potential to improve blood flow and enhance nitric oxide production, which may benefit overall circulation. 10. **Detoxification**: Lemon juice is often associated with aiding the body's natural detoxification processes, mainly due to its potential to support liver function. It's important to note that while these juices offer several health benefits, they should be consumed as part of a balanced diet. Drinking them in moderation is key to avoid excessive sugar intake, as some of these fruits can be naturally high in sugars. Additionally, if you have any specific health concerns or medical conditions, it's always a good idea to consult with a healthcare professional before making significant changes to your diet. #PomegranateJuice #AppleJuice #LemonJuice #HealthyChoices #Nutrition #HealthBenefits #ImmuneSupport #HeartHealth #Antioxidants #DigestiveHealth #Hydration #WeightManagement #SkinCare #NaturalDetox #HealthyLifestyle #Wellness #StayHealthy #HealthyDrinks #FruitJuice #DeliciousAndHealthy #HealthTips #HealthyLiving #NutritiousBeverages #FreshJuice #FruitPower #JuiceGoals #HealthyHabits #FruitMedley #StayHydrated #BoostYourHealth

Not just a weed‚Ä¶              Dandelions are an amazing medicinal plant and not just some annoying weed. All parts of the plant, from the flower to the stem to the root, are edible and healthy. What is special about the dandelion is the white milk juice, which is contained in its parts. The dandelion supplies the body with important vitamins and minerals and at the same time has a diuretic effect. It contains potassium so that our body can never suffer from a lack of nutrients. The medicinal plant against urinary tract infections is used as a homeopathic diuretic. Furthermore, regular consumption of dandelions can also prevent the formation of kidney stones. Exercise is important for several reasons: 1. Physical health: Regular exercise helps maintain a healthy weight, improves cardiovascular health, strengthens muscles and bones, and reduces the risk of chronic diseases such as heart disease, type 2 diabetes, and certain types of cancer. 2. Mental health: Exercise has been shown to improve mood, reduce symptoms of depression and anxiety, and enhance overall mental well-being. It can also improve sleep quality and boost cognitive function. 3. Energy levels: Engaging in regular physical activity increases energy levels and reduces feelings of fatigue. It improves endurance and stamina, making daily tasks and activities easier to perform. 4. Stress reduction: Exercise is a great stress reliever. It helps release endorphins, which are natural chemicals in the brain that act as mood elevators and reduce stress levels. It also provides a healthy outlet for pent-up emotions and tension. 5. Social interaction: Many forms of exercise, such as team sports or group fitness classes, provide opportunities for social interaction and can help build connections and friendships. This social aspect of exercise can contribute to overall happiness and well-being. 6. Cognitive function: Regular exercise has been linked to improved cognitive function, including better memory, attention, and problem-solving skills. It is also associated with a reduced risk of cognitive decline and dementia. Medwin Clinicians  Did You Know!!! Medicine: Beyond the Basics  Atrial Fibrillation. Why it is dangerous if not treated.  Atrial fibrillation, or AFib, occurs when the heart's upper chambers, called the atria, beat irregularly and often too fast. This can lead to a number of dangerous consequences. Normally, the heart's electrical signaling system regulates its rhythm. But with AFib, the signals get disrupted, causing chaotic and disorganized contractions. Why is AFib dangerous? Well, for one, it can increase your risk of stroke. Since the blood isn't being pumped effectively, it can pool and form clots in the heart, which can travel to the brain and cause a stroke. AFib can also weaken the heart over time, leading to heart failure. This happens because the irregular heartbeat doesn't allow the heart to pump enough blood to meet the body's needs. In addition, AFib can cause other complications like blood clots in other parts of the body, as well as dizziness, fatigue, and shortness of breath. It's crucial to understand that AFib is not a condition to be taken lightly. If left untreated, it can be life-threatening. There are many treatment options available for AFib, such as medication, cardioversion, catheter ablation, and surgery. If you experience any symptoms of AFib, it's important to see a doctor and get a diagnosis. This is Dr Edwin, If you have any questions or concerns, feel free to leave them in the comments below. Attention, guys! Did you know that Vitamin D3 can have some serious benefits for your health and hormones? Here are just a few: üí™ Testosterone: Studies have shown that low levels of Vitamin D3 are associated with lower testosterone levels in men. By supplementing with Vitamin D3, you may be able to boost your T levels and enjoy benefits like increased muscle mass, improved mood, and enhanced sexual function. ü¶¥ Bone Health: Vitamin D3 is essential for calcium absorption, which is crucial for maintaining strong bones and preventing osteoporosis. This is especially important for men as they age and are at greater risk for bone loss and fractures (make sure to take K2 with Vitamin D3). üß† Brain Function: Vitamin D3 may also play a role in cognitive function and reducing the risk of cognitive decline. One study even found that men with higher levels of Vitamin D3 had better memory and information processing abilities. So, what are the best sources of Vitamin D3? Sunlight is a great natural source, but many people don't get enough due to factors like climate, indoor lifestyles, and sunscreen use. Fortunately, you can also find Vitamin D3 in foods like fatty fish, egg yolks, and fortified dairy products(dairy is not a favorite source of D3 of mine because of all the hormones and other processing factors that come along with most fortified dairy in stores). If you're considering taking a Vitamin D3 supplement, be sure to consult with your doctor first to determine the best dose for your needs. Generally, 1,000-5,000 IU per day is a safe and effective range for most men. Remember, moderation is key! ü´ÄAngina vs. MI ü´Ä üî¥Angina = inadequate oxygen sent to the heart muscle due to narrowing of the coronary arteries. This causes *ischemia* ‚Äì may be precipitated by exertion, exercise, or stress. Angina should be relieved by rest and nitroglycerin.  ‚≠êPatients with history of angina should be encouraged to carry nitroglycerin tablets with them at all times (in their bag, purse, etc.) should chest pain occur Blockage/occlusion of a major vessel = NO blood flow, leading to an infarct (myocardial infarction) = death of the muscle ü´ÄMyocardial Infarction (MI) = heart attack! The muscle is receiving inadequate oxygen which causes death of the cardiac muscle. An MI is not relieved by rest or nitroglycerin and requires immediate intervention. EKGs will help give more information about the type of MI (STEMI vs. NSTEMI) and elevated cardiac biomarkers will be seen with an MI. ARE YOU AN ADRENALINE JUNKY? Adrenaline, a hormone produced by the adrenal glands, plays a crucial role in the body's fight-or-flight response. It heightens awareness, increases heart rate, and provides a sudden surge of energy during stressful situations, enabling quick, decisive actions. However, prolonged exposure to high levels of adrenaline due to chronic stress can lead to serious health issues. Excessive adrenaline can strain the heart, elevate blood pressure, weaken the immune system, and disrupt sleep patterns. It's linked to various diseases such as hypertension, heart disease, and weakened immunity, highlighting the importance of managing stress for overall well-being. #adrenaline #cortisol #adrenals #stress #wellness #nutrition #serenity #nutrition #destress #immunity #highbloodpressure #hypertension #heartdisease #heart #happy

#Hearthealth #Dietarychoices #Exerciseroutine Heart Health Section: The heart is one of the most vital organs in the human body, bearing a crucial responsibility in the circulatory system. The health of the heart has a profound impact on overall well-being, making it essential for everyone to prioritize understanding heart health. Here are some key points about heart health: 1.Maintain Healthy Eating Habits: Heart health is closely linked to dietary choices. Foods high in saturated fats, cholesterol, and calories can pose risks to heart health. Improper dietary habits can lead to elevated blood lipids, high blood pressure, and unstable blood sugar levels, increasing the risk of cardiovascular diseases. Therefore, it's important to reduce the consumption of high-fat, high-cholesterol, and high-calorie foods and incorporate a diet rich in nutritious options such as fruits, vegetables, fish, and nuts. 2.Establish a Regular Exercise Routine: Moderate physical activity can enhance cardiopulmonary function and elevate heart health. Engaging in at least 150 minutes of aerobic exercise per week can reduce the risk of heart diseases. Opt for low-intensity exercises like walking, jogging, swimming, and gradually increase the intensity and frequency based on your individual fitness level. 3.Control Blood Lipids: Elevated blood lipids are a significant risk factor for heart diseases. High levels of blood lipids can lead to arterial hardening, resulting in narrowed and weakened blood vessels, increasing the risk of heart health issues. To control blood lipids, focus on a low-fat and low-cholesterol diet, and incorporate regular physical activity while avoiding prolonged periods of sedentary behavior. 4.Quit Smoking and Limit Alcohol Intake: Both smoking and excessive alcohol consumption are detrimental to heart health. Nicotine and alcohol have damaging effects on the heart and blood vessels, leading to increased heart rate, elevated blood pressure, and coronary artery constriction, thereby increasing the risk of heart diseases. 5.Consistent Heart Health Checkups: Regular health checkups can help detect heart health issues early, including conditions like hypertension, arrhythmias, and atherosclerosis.  If you have a family history of heart diseases, experience high work-related stress, or maintain an irregular lifestyle, it is advisable to undergo more frequent heart health assessments.

News you can use! Part 4 for Heart Month: Let‚Äôs learn how to read the Nutrition Facts label. The label on packaging can be helpful, but I find the average consumer does not understand what they are reading. Let‚Äôs break it down. Here are my Top 6 Items to Watch on the Nutrition Facts Panel: 1. Serving Size 2. Calories per serving 3. Saturated 4. Added sugars 5. Fiber 6. Sodium Serving size is an important part of the label because if you don‚Äôt check the serving size, the rest of the numbers are meaningless. The information given, is for that serving size. If you eat half the serving, then you get half the nutrients, if you eat twice the serving, then you get double the nutrients.  DASH Diet is the best diet for heart health. It‚Äôs not meant to be weight loss diet. It‚Äôs a dietary plan low in saturated fat, low in sodium, and high in fiber, fruits & veggies.  I hope this mini-lesson helps! Searching for the perfect smoothie that not only delights your taste buds but also supports your heart health during Heart Health Month? Look no further! Our delectable berry smoothie is here to steal the spotlight on the last day of Heart Health Month! Bursting with heart-loving omega-3s, essential nutrients, and protein, this smoothie is a delicious way to show your heart some extra love. Ingredients: 1 cup frozen blueberries 1 ripe frozen banana 1/2 cup spinach leaves 1/2 cup Greek yogurt (or plant-based yogurt for a vegan option) 1 teaspoon Barlean's Forti-Flax 1 teaspoon Barlean's Organic Chia Seeds 1 tablespoon of Barlean's Seriously Delicious Blackberry Smoothie ¬Ω scoop vanilla protein powder of your choice (plant based if vegan!) ¬Ω - 1 cup water Instructions: 1.) In a blender, add the blueberries, banana, spinach leaves, Greek yogurt, ground flaxseeds, chia seeds, protein powder, Barlean's Seriously Delicious Blackberry Smoothie, honey or maple syrup (if using), and water. 2.) Blend all the ingredients together on high speed until smooth and creamy. If the smoothie is too thick, you can add more water until you reach your desired consistency. 3.) Taste the smoothie and adjust the sweetness if needed by adding honey or maple syrup. 4.) Pour the smoothie into glasses and garnish with a few fresh berries or a sprinkle of ground flaxseeds if desired. Serve immediately and enjoy the heart-healthy goodness! #hearthealth #hearthealthmonth #omega3 #smoothie #barleans #wellness

Natural ways to increase Nitric Oxide: Dietary Nitrate-Rich Foods: Consuming foods high in dietary nitrates boosts nitric oxide production. These foods include leafy greens (such as spinach, kale, and arugula), beetroot, celery, and other vegetables. L-arginine and L-citrulline: L-arginine and L-citrulline are amino acids that serve as precursors to nitric oxide synthesis in the body. Foods rich in these amino acids include nuts, seeds, legumes, meat, and seafood.  Regular Exercise: Physical activity, especially aerobic exercise, can stimulate nitric oxide production in the body. Exercise-induced increases in blood flow and oxygen demand trigger the release of nitric oxide, leading to vasodilation and improved circulation. Sunlight Exposure: Sunlight exposure to the skin stimulates the production of nitric oxide, which may contribute to the cardiovascular benefits associated with sunlight exposure. Spending time outdoors in natural sunlight can help increase nitric oxide levels in the body. Antioxidant-Rich Foods: Antioxidants help protect nitric oxide from oxidative damage and support its bioavailability in the body. Consuming a diet rich in antioxidant-containing foods, such as fruits, vegetables, nuts, seeds, and spices, help maintain optimal nitric oxide levels. Limiting Free Radical Damage: Oxidative stress and free radicals can impair nitric oxide synthesis and function in the body. Minimizing exposure to environmental toxins, reducing alcohol consumption, avoiding smoking, and managing stress can help protect nitric oxide levels from oxidative damage. Incorporating these lifestyle strategies and dietary interventions can help naturally increase nitric oxide levels in the body, promoting cardiovascular health, exercise performance, and overall well-being. #nitricoxide #hearthealth #dailyhealth #healthtips #nurse #nursepractitioner #fyp

HDL (High-Density Lipoprotein) is known as the "good" cholesterol because it helps remove other forms of cholesterol from your bloodstream. A clip from my talk a couple weeks ago at the Health & Fitness Expo. Sometimes we forget this but our body is doing everything it can to keep us in health or balance (homeostasis). The question is, are we supporting that process, or are we interfering with it? If you find yourself in a state of imbalance, take these 4 steps: 1. Anchor in your WHY. Write down the ways your health will improve your life and add quality to the lives of your loved ones. Revisit this often, but especially when it‚Äôs hard. 2. Address the root cause. Retrace your symptoms back to when they started. What foods were you frequently consuming? Who/what had influence on you? What were your stressors? What is/was your environment? 3. Stop the offenders. Inflammatory acidic foods, unmanaged chronic stress, toxic relationships‚Ä¶. the things that impose stress physically and mentally. 4. Change your environment. Create a healing, alkaline environment by bringing in an excess of anti-inflammatory foods (foods that love you back), movement you enjoy, supportive relationships‚Ä¶. Do more of what brings you peace. Even if medicine or medical intervention is needed, we must not forget to clean up our environment so we can enjoy our health long-term. #nutrition #antiinflammatory #wellness #healing #holistic #selfcare #health #healthylifestyle #heal #healthyliving #healingjourney #plantbased #cellhealth #detox #disease #diseaseprevention #cancer #inflammation #guthealth #heartdisease #diabetes #alkalinediet #alkaline #stress #balance #healthtips #holistichealth #holistichealing #mindbody #nutritionist

What is an echocardiogram? An echo test is an ultrasound of the heart. It uses high-frequency sound waves to produce images of the heart‚Äôs valves and chambers so that doctors can see how your heart functions. Echo tests are often combined with Doppler imaging technology to show how blood flows across the heart‚Äôs valves. Why did my doctor order an echocardiogram? Doctors might want to see an echocardiogram to investigate signs or symptoms of heart disease, like shortness of breath, chest discomfort, or swelling in the legs. They might also order an echocardiogram if something abnormal, like a heart murmur, is detected during an exam. It can help them see if there‚Äôs been damage to the heart muscle or a problem with a valve. How is an echocardiogram done? During the echo test, you‚Äôll be asked to put on a hospital gown. You‚Äôll lie on an exam table, and a sonographer or ultrasound tech will put some gel on the end of an ultrasound wand and move it along your chest. The gel might be a little cold, but you should not feel any major discomfort during the test. In some cases, doctors might need to inject a contrast agent into your bloodstream in order to see the borders of the heart better. When will I get my results? If your test was ordered by a cardiologist who can read their own echo test results, the doctor should be able to figure out quickly if anything abnormal is going on with your heart. If it‚Äôs been ordered by a non-cardiologist, they should get the official results to report within a day. Black women have a higher rate of hypertension-related heart disease and congestive heart failure in compared to other races.  * African-American women ages 20 and older, 49 percent have heart diseases. * Only 1 in 5 African-American women believes she is personally at risk. * Only 52 percent of African-American women are aware of the signs and symptoms of a heart attack. * Only 36 percent of African-American women know that heart disease is their greatest health risk. * More than 40 percent of non-Hispanic blacks have high blood pressure, which is more severe in blacks than whites. and develops earlier in life. Heart disease is the No. 1 killer of women can sometimes be a complication of breast cancer treatment. Older women who survive breast cancer are more likely to die of heart disease than a cancer recurrence. Some breast cancer treatments can affect the heart, making survivors more likely to develop cardiovascular disease. Radiation therapy to the chest or breast also increases the risk for early coronary artery disease. It can also damage the heart valves. Meds used in hormonal therapies can affect your heart, too. #breastcancer #heartdiseaseawareness #heartdiseaseandbreastcancer #blackwomenhealth #heartdiseaseprevention #heartdisease #holistichealth #wellnesstips #hearthealth #breastcancerawarenessüíï #breastcancerawareness #cardiovascularhealth #reducetheriskofheartdisease #reduceheartdisease

The zombie apocalypse is real, but it‚Äôs not the kind you imagine. Programmed cellular death, or apoptosis, clears out old or damaged cells and recycles parts for new cells. But sometimes cells don‚Äôt quite die. They become zombie cells or senescent cells. Zombie cells are caused by DNA damage, critically short telomeres, and chemical or toxic stress, including our inflammatory diet and lifestyle. They accelerate all age-related diseases: cancer, heart disease, liver disease, dementia, Parkinson‚Äôs, cataracts, arthritis, and muscle loss, or sarcopenia. Answer with Rationale: 1, 3, 5 	1.	Administer Atropine 0.5 mg IV push. 	‚Ä¢	Correct: Atropine is the first-line treatment for symptomatic bradycardia to increase the heart rate. 	2.	Place the patient in a Trendelenburg position. 	‚Ä¢	Incorrect: The Trendelenburg position is not indicated for sinus bradycardia. It is typically used to treat hypotension due to blood loss or shock. 	3.	Prepare for transcutaneous pacing if the patient becomes unstable. 	‚Ä¢	Correct: Transcutaneous pacing is a backup intervention for bradycardia if Atropine is ineffective, especially if the patient becomes hemodynamically unstable. 	4.	Discontinue the patient‚Äôs Lisinopril immediately. 	‚Ä¢	Incorrect: There is no indication to stop Lisinopril, which is used to manage hypertension. This should be evaluated by the healthcare provider. 	5.	Monitor the patient‚Äôs vital signs and reassess after 5 minutes. 	‚Ä¢	Correct: Monitoring and reassessing vital signs is crucial to determine the effectiveness of interventions and the patient‚Äôs response. 	6.	Educate the patient about the need for lifestyle modifications to manage hypertension. 	‚Ä¢	Incorrect: While important for long-term care, this is not an immediate priority in managing acute sinus bradycardia. #NursingStudents #NCLEXPrep #NursingSchool #SinusBradycardia #CardiacNursing #NurseLife #NursingEducation #NurseEducator #NursingReview #NCLEX2024 #NextGenNCLEX #MedicalEducation #CriticalCareNursing #NursingStudyTips #RNStudent #NursingGoals #NursingExam #NursingSkills #HealthcareEducation #NurseInspiration #FutureNurse #NursingSchoolStruggles #CardiacCare #NurseMentor #NursingInstructor #StudyNursing #NursingSimulation #NursingKnowledge #NursingPath #PassNCLEX‚Äù

A month of hospitals! As everyone knows on July 29th our son was in a terrible car crash. We spent a total of 19 days in hospitals. Home for a week and a half and Landyn had surgery on Tuesday morning and once we got home with him that afternoon is when my husband started not feeling right. 3 Tips to Lower your Cholesterol Levels Naturally 1. Eat more fiber. Fiber, particularly soluble fiber, may help lower LDL cholesterol levels. Foods that are good sources include oats, barley, beans, lentils, fruits, and veggies! It's also prime time for apples and peaches. An apple a day keeps the cholesterol away, Maybe?! 2. Choose heart healthy fats. I'm talking about the unsaturated fats which can be found in foods such as nuts, seeds, olive oil, and avocado. A little bit goes a long way. Enjoy some almonds in your oatmeal or sprinkle some pumpkin seeds on a baked potato. 3. Reduce saturated and trans fat. Reducing these two heavy hitters can make an impact on your cholesterol levels. "üåü Balancing Electrolytes: A Key to Holistic Wellness üåü In the grand symphony of our bodies, electrolytes play a crucial role. These tiny charged particles - sodium, potassium, calcium, magnesium - aren't just about keeping us hydrated; they're the conductors of our overall health orchestra. üé∂üíß üí° Let's break it down: 1Ô∏è‚É£ Mental Health: A balanced electrolyte profile fosters a balanced mind. Adequate levels help regulate neurotransmitters, promoting better mood and reducing stress. #MindBodyBalance #ElectrolyteCalm 2Ô∏è‚É£ Core Health: Our heart and muscles depend on electrolytes to function optimally. Potassium, for instance, helps maintain a healthy heart rhythm, while calcium keeps muscles strong. #HeartHealth #StrongMuscles 3Ô∏è‚É£ Bone Health: Calcium and magnesium aren't just for muscles; they're vital for strong bones too. Wellness IV Infusion Therapy Offers Atherosclerosis Chelation Therapy! Our Atherosclerosis Chelation Therapy Is A Therapy That Helps In The Removal Of Plaques From The Arterial Walls. It Is Used To Help Reduce Symptoms Associated With Cardiovascular Diseases Like Angina, High Blood Pressure, Arrhythmia, Shortness Of Breath, Stroke, And Pain In The Jaw, Throat, Neck, Upper Abdominal Or Back Areas. Atherosclerosis Chelation Therapy Can Be An Alternative To Other Invasive Procedures. . Atherosclerosis Chelation is the use of EDTA to help reduce the build up of plaque on arterial walls. EDTA also known as Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid is used for chelation to remove plaques from the arterial walls when stenosis which is a narrowing or occlusion which is a total blockage has taken place. There are many drugs used to stop, reverse, and prevent atherosclerosis. Many of these drugs require chemo-like monitoring by your physician. Chelation therapy on the other hand is a natural method that has no side effects if it is done properly by an accomplished Atherosclerosis Chelation Therapist. . Atherosclerosis usually starts at a generally young age and worsens as we continually age. It has been shown that almost all people have some degree of Atherosclerosis by the age of 65. Cardiovascular Disease is also the #1 cause of death and disabilities around the world. . Anyone who has cardiovascular disease or stenosis or occlusion of vascular arteries is a good candidate for atherosclerosis chelation therapy. This type of chelation can be an alternative and preventive therapy to invasive and sometimes dangerous surgeries. Prevention and lifestyle changes for younger individuals can save lives. Personalized management is key, especially for those with other risk factors like smoking or high blood pressure. Addressing a common & undertreated cause of anxiety: Did you know that an epidemiological study estimates that 55-60% of people 50 years old or older have part of their stomach jammed up into their chest cavity? The stomach is a very large thick muscular organ that resides on the same side of the body as the heart. When it gets pushed up into the chest cavity, it squishes the heart and reduces the amount of space the lungs have to expand. This can cause anxiety, arrhymias of the heart, chest pain, shortness of breath, reflux, gastrointestinal issues, scoliosis, and more. However, I move stomachs out of the chest cavity all the time with an external technique. Sometimes, when someone has a lot of scar tissue gluing the stomach in the wrong location, such as when there has been past surgery while the stomach was herniated, I have to give someone a series of wave therapy treatments before I do this. Otherwise, I can generally get the stomach all the way out of the chest cavity on the 1st or 2nd visit. Another great tool to have is a bottle of lavendar oil and an essential oil diffuser. Smelling lavendar has been found in studies to be an effective method of reducing anxiety. It is hypothesized that when a person smells lavender oil it effects receptors that cause the amygdala of the brain to signal the body that it is safe. Let‚Äôs work on bringing you to a higher quality of life where it is easier for you to do what you want to get done and easier for you to love your life. Oil pulling for dental health! Pro tip- Spit in trash to not clog your drain üòâü¶∑ Dating back over 3,000 years, oil pulling originated in India as a way to detoxify the body and promote oral health. The practice involves swishing a tablespoon of oil, typically coconut or sesame oil, in your mouth for 20 minutes before spitting it out. Not only does oil pulling help remove harmful bacteria and toxins from the mouth, but it has also been linked to fresher breath, whiter teeth, and healthier gums. Plus, it's an all-natural alternative to chemical-laden mouthwashes and teeth whitening products. So why not give oil pulling a try? Just remember to spit the oil out and rinse your mouth with water afterwards! #oilpulling #oralhealth #naturalhealth #ancientpractices #coconutoil #sesameoil #whiterteeth #healthylifestyle #freshbreath #healthytips #dentalcare #holistichealth #functionalmedicine #hearthealth #guthealth #microbiome

The Grinch may have congestive heart failure! üò¶ On a serious note, February is American Heart Month, and @yourbenefitsbesties is providing information and tips about heart health to help raise awareness! Today, we‚Äôre going to briefly discuss what an enlarged heart is... An enlarged heart (cardiomegaly) isn‚Äôt a disease, but rather a sign of another condition. The term ‚Äúcardiomegaly‚Äù refers to an enlarged heart seen on any imaging test, including a chest X-ray. Other tests are then needed to diagnose the condition that‚Äôs causing the enlarged heart. Enlarged heart, in heart failure If the heart weakens, as it can with heart failure, it begins to enlarge. This forces the heart to work harder to pump blood to the rest of the body. Heart damage and certain types of heart disease can cause an enlarged heart. Sometimes short-term stress on the body, such as pregnancy, can cause the heart to get larger. Depending on the condition, an enlarged heart may be temporary or permanent. Treatment for an enlarged heart may include medications, medical procedures or surgery. Symptoms In some people, an enlarged heart (cardiomegaly) causes no signs or symptoms. Others may have these signs and symptoms of cardiomegaly: Shortness of breath, especially while lying flat Waking up short of breath Irregular heart rhythm (arrhythmia) Swelling (edema) in the belly or in the legs To learn more, visit Mayo Clinic‚Äôs (@Mayo Clinic) at Mayoclinic.org. #YourBenefitsBesties #AmericanHeartMonth #FebruaryisAmericanHeartMonth #HeartMonth #HeartHealth #HeartAwareness #HeartAttack #Cardiologist #Cardiology #HealthMemes #DoctorMemes #NurseMemes #MedicalMemes #EnlargedHeart #CongestiveHeartFailure #Cardiomegaly #TheGrinch #TheGrinchMemes #TheGrinchEdit #BorisKarloff

Don‚Äôt let this happen to you! Keep your heart healthy by eating right, exercising, and minimizing stressful activities! February is almost here and it‚Äôs American Heart Month, so @YourBenefitsBesties are here to help raise awareness. Today, we‚Äôre going to focus on ways to help you minimize and manage stress! 1. Get out of the house. Take a walk outside and pay attention to the sights and sounds around you. 2. Practice healthy sleep routines. Try to go to bed and wake up at the same time each day. Unwind before bed by dimming the lights and avoiding alcohol and large meals. 3. Find physical activities and exercise that you like to do. Examples include walking, jogging, biking, yoga, lifting weights, playing sports, hiking, gardening, dancing, and playing with pets. 4. Take a break from screens. Set aside 1-2 times per day to check the news and social media. Enjoy screen-free meals with family and friends. 5. Meditation and breathing exercises. Taking deep breaths during a stressful situation can help you quiet your mind and make better decisions. Practicing meditation and mindfulness can help lower overall stress. 6. Start a new hobby. Try learning a new instrument, signing up for a class, cooking a new recipe, drawing, painting, volunteering, visiting a museum, camping, or listening to new music. 6. Reach out to your network. Connect with friends, family, and co-workers throughout the week, and make plans to spend time together doing activities you enjoy. Are eggs a heart disease risk? Note: On YouTube I received some fair critique that the review I cite in the video is funded by the egg industry. Since this is a touchy subject for some, the results of this review were confirmed in an independent analysis (PMID: 32635569). In these analyses, eating 3 eggs per day led to an 8-9 point increase in LDL. However, these analyses are also skewed in that they included studies of hyper-responders, thereby driving the effect upward. I would wager the true increase in most people (non-hyper-responders) would be more mild, although still present (at 3 eggs per day). Eating eggs 1-2 times per week likely has no effect. Finally, these analyses not only include dietary cholesterol, but saturated fat, so the direct effect of dietary cholesterol (based on other studies), itself, is likely negligible. Hope it eases some minds. :)  #heartdisease #heartdiseaseawareness #hearthealth #eggs #healthtip #nutritiontip #nutritiontips #healthtips #healthtipsoftheday

Most talk, I follow through.  ‚ÄúLive the Life, You Preach!‚Äù  Table of Contents: ¬∑       Chapter 1: Foundations of Longevity o   Aging is an inevitable journey, one that is as complex as it is universal. To understand longevity, one must first grasp the biological mechanisms that underpin aging. This chapter aims to explore the intricate interaction of cellular and molecular processes that not only orchestrate our progression through life but also the manner and tempo at which we age. We'll cast light upon the various factors that contribute to aging and delve into both historical perspectives and groundbreaking topics of research that aim to decode the lifespan. ¬∑       Chapter 2: The Power of Diet o   Imagine your body as a high-performance vehicle. The food you eat represents the quality of fuel you supply it. Good choices support a smooth ride and longevity, while poor choices can cause breakdowns and wear out the engine faster. In this chapter, we venture into a dietary approaches, that are pivotal for preserving youthfulness and extending lifespan.   ¬∑       Chapter 3: Unveiling the Pantheon of Age-Defying Supplements ‚Äì Expanded Insights o   The pursuit of anti-aging interventions frequently includes the exploration of dietary supplements thought to enhance longevity and minimize the biological impacts of aging. Here, we expand on several supplements drawing attention for their potential age-defying properties and the substantial research efforts backing them. ¬∑       Chapter 4: Exercise and Longevity - Vitality's Pillar o   Studies suggest that various forms of exercise contribute differently to our longevity. Cardiovascular exercises bolster the heart and reduce risks of metabolic diseases, resistance training maintains muscle and bone health, and flexibility and balance exercises support functional independence. Together, they create a comprehensive exercise regimen that not only adds years to life but life to years. ¬∑       Chapter 5: Lifestyle Adjustments for Longevity ‚Äì A Holistic Blueprint o   Enhancing longevity through lifestyle adjustments involves a multifaceted approach that aligns traditional wisdom with modern scientific insights. The following are evidence-based strategies that underscore the profound impact of sleep, stress management, social engagement, lifelong learning, and habit reformation on extending life expectancy. ¬∑       Chapter 6: The Repurposing of Common Medications for Longevity o   The exploration of existing medications for potential longevity and anti-aging benefits has become a fascinating avenue for recent research. üí• WHAT‚ÄôS YOUR DIAGNOSIS? üí•ü©∫  Correct diagnosis: Left Ventricular Free Wall rupture is a life threatening complication, most commonly occurring in patients with myocardial infarction. It can also occur in the setting of trauma and infection. Color Doppler imaging helps visualize ventricular free wall rupture by detecting abnormal flow patterns, such as blood leaking through the ruptured wall. In cases of rupture, there may be a turbulent flow of blood between the ventricular chambers or into the pericardial space, which can be visualized as a distinct color flow signal on the echocardiogram, indicating the presence and location of the rupture. Patients present with chest pain, cold extremities, mental status changes, as well as symptoms of cardiac tamponade (hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and distended neck veins). Differential diagnoses include papillary muscle rupture, aortic dissection, and ventricular pseudo aneurysm.  #fyp #medicalstudent #collegevlog #premed  #motivation #hearthealth   #healthtips #viral  #medicine  #lifestyle #fitness #student #college #cardio #echo #premed #cardiology #diagnosis #casestudy #doppler #trauma

Medicine: Beyond the Basics Blood pressure checks High blood pressure, also known as hypertension, is a dangerous medical condition that affects millions of people around the world. When your doctor takes your blood pressure, they measure two numbers in particular - systolic and diastolic. A normal reading should be less than 120/80. An elevated blood pressure reading is over 130/85. This means that your heart is having to work too hard to pump blood around your body. Left untreated, high blood pressure can lead to a range of serious health problems, including strokes, heart attacks and kidney failure. That‚Äôs why it‚Äôs so important to monitor your blood pressure regularly and take steps to keep it under control. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî üè° 4850 W oakland park blvd, Ste 224. Time lapse animation of what happens inside a coronary artery in the years and months before a heart attack. Multiple risk factors (as well as genetics) contribute to the plaque build up which if left untreated can result in a rupture of this plaque inside the artery (think of a zit popping), causing thrombus formation and occlusion. This is when a stent is used to fix the blockage - but is simply a local solution to the sequelae of a systemic problem. The best strategy is to aim to prevent it in the first place by impacting the modifiable risk factors that you have some control over, which may be accomplished by lifestyle measures, meds or both. Once you have had a first event however the game changes and meds + lifestyle changes are both mandatory! (If you want the best shot of preventing a second event) #cardiology #medicine #hearthealth #heartattack #healthylifestyle #medtok

Is period pain normal?  Cramping is because your uterus is a muscle, and it cramps to contract, helping you shed your uterine lining.  What I‚Äôve found is that magnesium deficiency can worsen cramping. Your heart, also a muscle, is at risk during low blood magnesium levels, increasing heart attack chances.  Magnesium is a nutrient rarely consumed enough in diets. Incorporating other electrolytes, like potassium, is beneficial. Think about it: when you have a leg cramp, you take potassium or eat a banana.
